{"questionId":"22257634","questionHtml":"<p>Consider the differential equation <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>y</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>x</mi><mi>y</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></math>, given that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math> when <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>.</p>\n<p>Use Euler’s method with step size <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn></math> to find the approximate value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi></math> when <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>attempt at Euler&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong> (M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>y</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>y</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>×</mo><msub><mi>y</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong><img src=\"__IMG__/5e1d7101a855eeae14eaa2bbc5f77000c01430db.png\" width=\"636\" height=\"46\"></strong></em>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong><em>&nbsp;(A1)</em></strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Any correct value either as a separate calculation or as part of a table, (including the result).</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>88</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>87603</mn><mo>…</mo></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[4 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"22257634","referenceCode":"24M.1.AHL.TZ2.7","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Consider the differential equation dydx=xy-1, given that y=2 when x=1. Use Euler’s method with step size 0.1 to find the approximate value of y when x=1.5.","paper":"1","level":"AHL","questionNumber":"7","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 4]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 5—Calculus","Topic 5—Calculus","AHL 5.16—Eulers method for 1st order DEs"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}